{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S1hKxhBZ8ggtCE2EnnTvjU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n- TLS secret `es-http-tls` has `ca.crt`, `tls.crt`, `tls.key`\n- Password secret `elastic-password` has password `elasticpass`\n\nI need to deploy:\n1. A ConfigMap for Elasticsearch configuration\n2. A headless Service for the StatefulSet (internal cluster communication)\n3. A Service named `es-http` for HTTPS access on port 9200\n4. A StatefulSet with 3 Elasticsearch nodes using the TLS secret and password\n\nKey Elasticsearch 8.x configuration points:\n- Security is enabled by default, so I need to configure TLS for the HTTP layer and inter-node transport communication\n- I'll set the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable from the secret\n- The ConfigMap will define the cluster name, network binding, and discovery seed hosts pointing to each node in the StatefulSet via the headless service DNS names\n\nWriting Elasticsearch config... In Elasticsearch 8.x with security enabled, transport layer TLS is mandatory, so I need to decide whether to use the same certificates for both HTTP and transport or generate separate ones. The certificates need proper SANs for node-to-node communication, and I could either reuse the existing TLS secret or create a self-signed approach, though a three-node cluster requires proper discovery configuration rather than single-node mode. I can use the same certificate for both transport and HTTP layers since I can set the verification mode to just check the certificate without strict hostname validation. Now I'm planning the Kubernetes resources: a ConfigMap for the Elasticsearch configuration, a headless Service for internal pod DNS resolution, an HTTP Service for external access on port 9200, and a StatefulSet with three replicas. For the configuration file, I'm setting up the cluster name and network host settings.\n\nConfiguring security and SSL... Writing the Kubernetes manifests... Writing config YAML... Writing Kubernetes manifests... Refining the readiness probe approach...\n\nI should verify that Elasticsearch automatically uses pod names as node identifiers in StatefulSets, and make sure the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting includes all three nodes for proper cluster bootstrap. With security enabled, the `elastic` user and its password are handled automatically through the environment variable. I'm also considering adding a PodDisruptionBudget to maintain cluster stability during disruptions.\n\nLet me focus on getting the core resources working first and then iterate from there. I'm creating a ConfigMap with the Elasticsearch configuration that sets up the cluster name, discovery mechanism, and security settings with TLS certificates.\n\nWriting manifest resources... Writing Kubernetes manifest...\n\nI need to think through the `vm.max_map_count` setting for Elasticsearch and how node naming works in StatefulSets. Since we're using a StatefulSet, each pod gets a predictable hostname like `elasticsearch-0`, `elasticsearch-1`, etc., which Elasticsearch will use as the node name by default. For the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` configuration in ES 8.x, I need to reference these actual node names rather than pod IPs.\n\nI should also reconsider the custom `elasticsearch.yml` config—when providing our own configuration, we're overriding ES 8's default security setup, so I need to make sure security settings are explicitly configured. Let me set the `node.name` field explicitly using the pod hostname to ensure consistency.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":196,"cache_read_input_tokens":29236,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":196},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null