{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0171VcyXV7wc95ue3dXvt2YS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The ES node can't resolve `es-headless`. This is because the headless service was just created and DNS might not be resolving properly yet. Let me check what full DNS the pods should use:\n\nIn Kubernetes, a headless service creates DNS entries like:\n- `es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` for the service itself\n- `elasticsearch-0.es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` for each pod\n\nSo `discovery.seed_hosts` should use the full qualified name or at least the FQDN within the namespace. Let me update the config to use `es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`.\nActually, even the short name `es-headless.elasticsearch` should work since the pod is in the same namespace. The real problem might be that the headless service doesn't have any endpoints yet when the first pod starts up, so DNS can't resolve it until the pod reaches Running state. I need to clarify the DNS behavior for headless services in Kubernetes - specifically whether they include not-ready pods or only ready ones, and how this applies to StatefulSets with their pod-specific DNS records like `pod-name.service-name`.\n\nThe core issue is that using just the service name in discovery resolves to the service endpoint, which returns no IPs if no pods are ready yet. I can fix this by either explicitly listing individual pod FQDNs, enabling `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service, or using the full service FQDN. Let me update the ConfigMap and Service configuration to use `publishNotReadyAddresses: true` along with individual pod FQDNs for more reliable discovery during startup.\n\nUpdating manifest with full FQDNs... no pods are ready yet, so DNS can't resolve the service. This creates a deadlock where the readiness probe fails because ES can't form a cluster, which prevents pods from becoming ready in the first place. I need to break this cycle by either relaxing the initial readiness requirements or using a different discovery mechanism that doesn't depend on all pods being ready first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1063,"cache_read_input_tokens":37091,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1063},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"68016074-feed-4e8b-9668-86d7b85ef721","uuid":"59f3c872-97c8-48c0-9963-b5ac345e1fba","request_id":"req_011CccEsvvhvC4ZbcTp3SzEf"}
